<font color="#FF0000">INFO</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct  8 15:57:08 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br>
I understand your quest for answers and information.  Vietnam was definitely a war of numbers as well as other things.  I've been searching official studies, Government records, Unit histories, military evaluations on tactics, the Combat Area Casualty File etc. etc. for approximately thr last 6 years.<br>
What makes the analysis of the Vietnam expereince so tough?  The time and place you served!!!  The war had extremes, from the World War I style trenches of the Marines at Con Thien, to the everlasting swamp and marsh of the Delta, where any hole more than a foot deep fills with water.  From the early war days of Viet Cong terroristic and insurgency warefare to the later war period of organized NVA battalions and regiments with mortar, sapper, anti-aircraft and rocket support.  Vietnam is a war of a million truths and and experiences.  For instance, helicopter and truck units with higher monthly loses than infantry.  I don;t believe that one could lump all Vietnam combat experiences into neat categories.  Vietnam was a war of unique nature.<br><br>
The VA performed a study of Nam vets that found out that 70% of those sampled experienced exposure to combat. (Dept of Labor-Bureau of Labor Statistics:  1990 Unemployment situation of Vietnam era Veterans)<br><br>
But what is combat?  Stanley Karnow reported in VIETNAM A HISTORY that combat was only coming under some kind of attack, ANY kind of attack, mortar, sniper, artillery, rocket, fire fight etc.  Stanley Karnow reports that 76% of Americans reported being under attack by enemy rockets and mortars and 56% had seen Americans killed or wounded.  The question here is how many Americans engaged enemy units in the field?  The high number of reported combat exposure probabely comes from the high incidents of mortar and rocket attack especially on big bases.  (No shame in combat exposure being limited to mortars and rockets, considering that Artillery was the #1 killer and #1 wounding force in World War II)<br><br>
In regards to combat exposure, the lenght of fire fights, and frequency to attack by the enemy, I searched long and hard for the answers to that for years (VA and Dept of Defense has too).  There are no set or definite answers.  That depends on when you where in-country and where.  I've begun my own informal polling of veterans to see, it certainly is a unresearched topic.  The true answers may be very difficult to find considering the length of the war and the various conditions of combat in Vietnam.  Fighting the Viet Cong generally meant ambushes, hit and run enemy tactics, and booby traps, but VC certainly fought as regiments, companies and battalions too.  For example, VC regiments ovveran the Dong Xoai Green Beret camp killing three Green Berets and two Seabees.  The NVA mostly fought as complete units in massive battles, but also had sapper teams and insurgency teams, as well as snipers.  So, you see the problem in diagnosing ombat exposure accross the board.<br><br>
One Army infantryman, CPL John Clancey, a veteran of 196th Infantry Brigade in I corps in 1967 summed up his experiences (compare these with your own), &quot;Most patrols are boring.  Some led to fights, about 3 in 10, but they were small ones.  Really large fights happened less than 10% of the time.&quot;<br><br>
Here is dome other info on combat that may be helpful to you:<br>
80% of all firefights were initiated by the enemy.  (James Gibson, The Perfect War:Technowar in Vietnam: Atlantic Monthly Press 1986)<br>
According to the Dept of Defense study of mid 1967, American forces had intiated combat just 14.3% of the time, while the enemy had iniated combat 78.6% of the time.  (Alain Enthoven, Memorandum for the Sec of Defense, 4 May 1967 in the Senator Gravel Edition: The Pentagon Papers p462)<br><br>
The most revealing piece of evidence on combat comes from the November 1993 Combat Area Casualty File, the Dept of Defense database on Vietnam War deaths.<br>
Here is a breakdown of the deaths from all branches for all reasons hostile and non-hostile (accident-illness).<br><br>
Army      38,190 deaths <br>
Marines   14,836 deaths<br>
Air Force  2,583 deaths<br>
Navy       2,553 deaths<br>
Coast Guard    7 deaths<br><br>
Here are the breakdown of the 58,169 deaths (all branches total) into euphamistic terms and categories as used by the Dept of Defense. Bear in mind that 47,244 deaths are from enemy action there rest are non-hostile.<br><br>
Causes  and Totals deaths from cause               <br>
Small Arms   18,487<br>
Multiple Fragmentation Wounds   8,458<br>
Air crash on land  7,989<br>
Other explosive device  7,446<br>
Artillery, Rocket, Mortar  4,913<br>
Other accident  1,373<br>
Misadventure  1,326<br>
Drowned/Suffocated  1,206<br>
Vehicle loss/crash  1,186<br>
Accidental homocide  943<br>
Accidental self destruction  842<br>
Other causes   749<br>
Air crash at sea  576<br>
Unknown  530<br>
Burns 530<br>
Illness/disease  495<br>
Suicide  382<br>
Heart Attack 274<br>
Intentional Homocide 230<br>
Malaria  118<br>
Bomb Explosion 52<br>
Stroke 42<br>
Hepatitis  22<br>
Please note that Misadventure is generally &quot;friendly fire&quot;  (another misconception since no fire enemy or fiendly is ever &quot;friendly), Homocides were mostly fraggings and Other Explosive Devices are booby traps and land mines.  Multiple Fragmentation wounds are the modern &quot;correct&quot; term for shrapnel, from any source.  Therefore the Combat Area Casualty file is misleading since a man killed by a enemy antipersonnel mine  can be labeled either Mutiple Fragmentation wounds or Other Explosive Device.<br><br>
In regards to wounds-303,704 men were wounded in action.  81% of men wounded in battle survived.<br>
Small arms accounted for 51% of deaths and 16% of the wounded.<br>
Fragments (shrapnel) Multiple Fragmentation wounds accounted for 36% of deaths and 65% of wounded.  Other explosive devices (boobytraps) accounted for 11% of deaths and 15% of wounded.<br>
Small Arms death percentages (51%) were higher in Vietnam than in World War II (32%) and in Korea (33%).<br><br>
Well, that's enough for now, if you want any more specific info, please, let me know.  I can even give info on enemy tactics.  Let me know your specific questions and I can see what I have information wise.  Maybe I can e-mail some info to you too.<br><br>
Cook, my dad was a Seabee in Vietnam, he served around Bien Hoa and the III corps area in support on Vietnamization (as an advisor) and in support of Army operations.  The Seabees are always willing to help any poor Marines that need help.  As the son of a Seabee, I'll still help any Poor Marines out there.  Just fooling around! :)<br><br>
Hey Cook, here is a little info for a decent Marine like yourself to use when ever some Army types (no offense to the Army) want to put the Marines down.  ONLY 26 Marines were captured by the enemy in NAM.  Marines are not much for surrendering.  54 Marines won Medals of Honor.<br>
Marine Medal of Honor breakdown by units:<br>
4th Regiment  10 Medals of Honor<br>
9th Regiment  8 Medals of Honor<br>
7th Regiment  7 Medals of Honor<br>
5th Regiment  6 Medals of Honor<br>
Recon and Force Recon 6 Medals of Honor<br>
3rd Regiment  5 Medals of Honor<br>
1st Regiment  5 Medals of Honor<br>
All other units, aviation, engineer etc.  7 Medals of Honor<br><br>
In regards to the Liberty Bridge, it was the largest built by Americans in Nam.  The Bridge was 2,040 long and took more than five months to build in 1967.  The job was handled by Mobile Construction Battalion 4, commanded by Commander Richard M. Fluss.  The Seabees used 5 tons of 10 inch nails, 5,000 24 inch bolts and 800 80ft long pilings that were driven 40 feet into the riverbed, allowing the bridge to stand 32 feet above the low water mark (a necessity with the monsoon high flow of water).  The Viet Cong dropped two spans of it which were repaired in just 32 hours.  I can give info of the Seabee Veterans of America and the Seabee Historical Foundation which have names and addresses of Seabees that worked on the Liberty Bridge.
